pull_request.title: feat: Implement comprehensive modeling framework with GUI
pull_request.body:
This commit delivers a complete, feature-rich hydraulic and hydrological modeling framework, built in response to user requests for a Preissmann-based model and a rapid modeling tool.

The project was developed in three main stages:

1.  **1D Hydraulic Model (`preissmann_model`)**:
    - A stable and verified model that solves the Saint-Venant equations using the implicit Preissmann scheme.
    - Includes support for hydraulic structures like `Gate` and `Pump` as internal boundary conditions.

2.  **Coupled Modeling Framework (`common` package)**:
    - A `BaseModelComponent` interface and `SimulationController` allow for connecting different model types (e.g., hydrological and hydraulic) into a single simulation.
    - Supports network topologies, including converging and diverging branches via a `Junction` component. This framework can handle any directed acyclic graph of model components.

3.  **Rapid Modeling GUI & Interface**:
    - A GUI built with the `eel` library for visually building model networks by dragging and dropping components, editing their properties, and defining connections.
    - A YAML configuration file format for defining models and networks without code.
    - A `ConfigParser` that reads the YAML file and automatically builds the simulation.
    - A generic `run_from_config.py` script to execute models directly from the configuration file.
    - The GUI provides real-time feedback during simulations, including a live log and a live plot of results. It also allows for post-simulation analysis and plotting.

The project is fully documented with a GUI manual and a comprehensive case study to demonstrate its capabilities.

Wow, I'm actually offended, I didn't think that was possible. Yes, I knew about the hardware issues. Yes, I knew that you can't pull enough pixels from a QVGA frame to get reliable recognition. That's why I'd been working on the updates to the esp32-camera driver I'd needed in order to allow the AotE code to be able to pull full-resolution frames from the GC2145 even without hardware JPEG output.

Not particularly inclined to continue that work when you close my tracking ticket without even bothering to talk to me, though. If you're happy with the current solution of "tell people they bought the wrong camera module", then this isn't a project I have any interest in contributing to after all.

If anyone else feels like picking up the work, the key is to use the 2145's windowing and subsampling registers to restrict the fetch to only a single QVGA-sized patch at one time. For streaming/reference image purposes, these can be stitched together into a full UXGA frame in software before encoding to jpeg and sending to the browser; for recognition purposes, a QVGA subframe aligned to a ROI has more than enough resolution to recognize a digit or two or three, even if you end up needing to pull multiple subframes to capture all the ROIs.

commits.message:
hw/core: Introduce administrative power-state property and its accessors

Some devices cannot be hot-unplugged, either because removal is not meaningful
(e.g. on-board devices) or not supported (e.g. certain PCIe devices). Others,
such as CPUs on architectures like ARM, lack native hotplug support but can
still have their availability controlled through host policy. In all these
cases, a mechanism is needed to track and control a deviceâ€™s *administrative*
power state â€” independent of its runtime operational state â€” so QEMU can:

  - Disable a device while keeping it described in firmware, ACPI, or other
    configuration.
  - Prevent guest use until explicitly re-enabled.
  - Coordinate transitions with platform-specific power handlers and migration
    logic.

This patch introduces the core qdev support for administrative power state â€”
defining the property, enum, and accessors â€” without yet applying it to any
device. Later patches in this series integrate it with helper APIs
(qdev_disable(), qdev_enable(), etc.) and specific device types such as CPUs,
completing the flow with platform-specific handlers.

Key additions:
  - New enum DeviceAdminPowerState with ENABLED, DISABLED, and REMOVED states,
    defaulting to ENABLED.
  - New DeviceClass flag admin_power_state_supported to advertise support for
    administrative transitions.
  - New QOM property "admin_power_state" to query or set the state on supported
    devices.
  - Internal accessors device_get_admin_power_state() and
    device_set_admin_power_state() to manage state changes, including safe
    handling when the device is not yet realized.

The enum models *policy* rather than electrical or functional power state, and
is distinct from runtime mechanisms (e.g. PSCI for ARM CPUs). The actual
operational state of a device is maintained by platform-specific or device-
specific code, which enforces runtime behaviour based on the administrative
setting. Every device starts administratively ENABLED by default. A DISABLED
device remains logically present but blocked from operation; a REMOVED device
is logically absent.
